tal\npassport.','recr7GNJJiUL0nTrx, recpMTkcK0iPRA7hx','','','','',''),(459,'recUAPmfMcKTC46RP','Identify Audience','Toolboxes','By just taking a few minutes to write down the different types of people who you\'re trying to reach, and what type of information they\'re looking for, you will enable you and your team to think much more strategically about the content they produce and distribute.\n','recK6y8mwbpqmNKEv','','','','',''),(460,'recKnNqI0jX0uLL0X','identity','glossary','','','recXG5ipz8hVUIwJ6','','','',''),(461,'recXLRCVpMtALpXm8','Imagery','data','','','','','','',''),(462,'rectNdQEwJqW4D4dU','Imagery','Tags','','recuonNXVQCAV91A8, recqFKhShTLzHRUIe, rec31FCztnFm0NNgB, rec0BbSfh3O9rsmyu','rec4ZShmUvNQdeCaD, recXpLfiYLY6Tyap5, recUTH4XXBPCYf2aj','recM0tpwsTeSKPdik','','',''),(463,'recDfY2UZj521EIWn','Imagery','glossary','pictures of an area or situation','recLy08xrAyPk6uZm','recq1o2ejJo5HPMbK','','','',''),(464,'recR1Pd0C2lOTL6BL','Import and Export OPML Libraries with TinyTinyRSS','Tutorials','TinyTinyRSS makes working with OPML libraries very easy.\n\nOPML is an XML-based outlining syntax that makes it very easy to move large collections of RSS feeds and their associated setting between feed reading systems.  For example, if you had 30 feeds from a disaster recovery coalition organization, you could export those feeds as a single OPML file and then import that file into another reader.  That reader would automatically subscribe to all those feeds, and associate those feeds with the same categories that were defined in the OPML file.  This makes RSS feed libraries super portable and awesome.  \n\n\n\nHere\'s a brief step by step guide for how to do it.\n\n\n\nLog into your TinyTinyRSS.\nGo to \"Actions>Preferences\"\nGo to the \"Feeds\" tab and select the OPML accordian menu on the bottom of the page.\nGive the file a name and click \"Export OPML\".\n\n\nTo import an OPML library, follow steps 1-3 described above but instead of step 4, click \"Browse\", select the appropriate OPML file and them click \"Import my OPML\".  It will automatically add the Feed along with whatever settings are associate with them, such as their catagories, to your feeds.','recQZtGMy5sgFvIRi','recaUFitVcT2hhzYo, recn2Fe6mUozKtlNU','','','',''),(465,'recLvTMjhzXrnq6UR','Importing Contacts into CiviCRM','Tutorials','There are two ways to input contacts into CiviCRM.\n\nAdding contacts through the CiviCRM application\nPlacing your contacts into a spreadsheet and then importing the spreadsheet into CiviCRM.\n\n\nTo add contacts through the CiviCRM application:\n\nLog into your CiviCRM.  If you\'re using Drupal, this requires logging into your Drupal site and then clicking a button in your navigation menu titled \'CiviCRM\'.\nFind the CiviCRM navigation bar.  It\'s probably on the top of your screen.  It\'s buttons include: \'Home\', \'Search\', \'Contacts\'... etc.\nClick on the \'Contacts\' button and a drop down menu will appear.  Click on \"New Individual.\"\nFill out as many fields as you want.  You\'ll have an opportunity to add groups and tags to contacts later.\nClick \'Save\'\n\n\nCongratulations!  You just created your first contact.\n\n\n\nIf you have more than 20 contacts to add to CiviCRM, you will probably save time by putting your contacts into a spreadsheet and then uploading that speadsheet into your CiviCRM system.  The first step is to start with a spreadsheet that is formatted to be imported into CiviCRM.  The easiest way to create such a spreadsheet is to export a few contacts from your CiviCRM, open it, delete the contact information and keep the fields.\n\nClick \'Search\' on top of your CiviCRM navigation menu and click \'Find Contacts.\'\nDon\'t fill out the fields, click \'search.\'\nYou should have a list of the contacts in your CiviCRM system.  Select them all, click on the drop down menu, select \'export\' and click \'go.\'\nSelect \'Export PRIMARY fields\' and click continue.  The system will download your export file. \nOpen the file with your computer\'s spreadsheet program.  We\'ll assume it\'s \"LibreOffice Calc.\"\nOnce LibreOffice has booted up, it will give you a \'Text Import\" window.  BEFORE you click \'OK\' you MUST click the check box entitled \'Seperated by: Comma\" under the \'Seperator options\' section.  Once you\'ve clicked that box, click \'OK\'.  The spreadsheet should open.\nLook at the top of the spreadsheet\'s window.  If it says \'read only\' you need to \'Save As\' the spreadsheet to your computer.\n\n\nNow you can enter information into the appropriate cells on your spreadsheet.  You do not need to fill out all the cells.  In fact, you can delete the columns you don\'t want to fill in.  We suggest deleting the everything before \'First Name\' and everything between \'Birth Date\' and \'Current Employer\' to make life simpler.\n\n\n\nNow it\'s time to import your full, nicely formatted spreadsheet into your CiviCRM.  Make sure you have deleted the contacts you had initially imported and make sure your second row is filled with information.\n\nSave your file in a CVS format.  This means the file\'s title will end with .csv.\nGo to your CiviCRM, click the \'Contacts\' menu item and click \'Import Contacts.\'\nSelect your file in the Upload CSV File field.\nDoes your first row contains headers and not contact information?  If so, click the first check box.\nLeave everything else as it is and click \'Continue.\'\nIn this area you need to match your \'Column Names\' on the left with the \'matching CiviCRM field\' on the right.  NOTES: (a) If your import rows are blank, it\'s because you first few rows don\'t have content.  Click \'Previous\', go back to your spreadsheet, delete the blank rows on top of your spreadsheet, save and reimport the sheet. (b) Do not map \'current employers\' because it will cause an error. (c) If you filled out a field that doesn\'t have a corresponding CiviCRM field and still want to import it, consider mapping it to the \'Note\' field.  \nIf you plan to add more contacts in the future with the same spreadsheet format, click \'save this field mapping.\'  Click \'Continue\'\nMake sure you\'re importing the same amount of rows that you have in your spreadsheet (minus the column headers).\nAdd these contacts to the appropriate groups and tags.  Click \'Import Now.\'  Click \'Ok\'.\nIf an error appears, check to make sure that your contacts haven\'t imported anyway before trying again.  Imported contacts don\'t always show up in the \'recent items\' feed on the left of your CiviCRM so make sure to search for a contact that you imported to see if everything works.  Sometimes it works, even if it says it didn\'t. :)\n\n\nResources\n\nCiviCRM Importable Spreadsheet CSV: ........\nExporting Data: http://wiki.civicrm.org/confluence/display/CRMDOC40/Exporting+Data\nImporting Data: http://wiki.civicrm.org/confluence/display/CRMDOC40/Importing+Data\nImporting Data into CiviCRM (via FlossManuals.net): http://en.flossmanuals.net/civicrm/ch019_importing/','recI1bc212RVK7aKK, recdZk6CZiTywlVag','recZHSZypSFHafKIW','','','',''),(466,'recB29yIctRumfXbZ','IMS','glossary','','','recPxlJDZ9xvTIQzX','','','',''),(467,'recjeGdrazTlv7Klg','incident mapping','glossary','','','rec4xRnv7vjttslFc','','','',''),(468,'recyZBwEsr24TjOqD','independent usage','glossary','','','recGLbkJq8DMb1Vqe','','','',''),(469,'recPEfApEOZp65vWu','industrial','glossary','','','rec3hwS1GjNy3eghU','','','',''),(470,'recYnT9GogRJ2Spou','Industry Innovation and Infrastructure','SDG','','','recLZ4kKaXm9NzMPn, recuTzltCTSSG5oiT, rec5ECE7TrKMUkCaN, recnrnLdt89foXkpd, recOFaQ5Qb7069XqA, recO7o9WVvC2oowhN, recHteUVQ9M3BXV7w, rechbISJhFEySprVr, reccEGzVMPWzVh0JP, recErG2MUxANSWBJk, recM2XJddaSgIBuKp, recBav9aEKklHjMaV, recEOFP1tUQ1gAN25, recBRw30Cs2zjBsle, receqqigIUe2Hm5lw, recBGeA3fA0ajaXgC, recdEInugFYktw0WM, reccdat48jl16RJ2u, recRGlnpr8YAFl9Tf, rec9QLNLnj9F1V5y8, recZihoX7mf8buPBY, reczWJ5vpbWvygQsu, recvI2hWHybhGygrI, recYWsqt3F55OI7jU, recN