 Aspiration 2016','Notes','What does a disaster look like?\n\nWhere does the data starrf? Where does patient tracking start? Collect data and then move it. Need infrastructure to do it. Set up your own infrastructure.\n\nThe first question to ask is who is doing what where?\n\nPhase 1 tends to be managing dead people.\n\nPhase 2 there is mapping to figure out where open routes are for help.\n\nPhase 3 need to process local information.\n\nPhase 4 there is cascading issues that come after the response.\n\nPhase 5 economic sustainability of the people.\n\nPhase 6 dealing with politics and corruption.\n\nDisasters are almost never the same. What are the templates we can embed that we can get official agencies to adopt so collaboration between people is possible.\n\nHow about individuals helping on the ground? How can we connect on-the-ground to action off-site/globally.\n\nIs remote action ever helpful? Lots of energy gets wasted.\n\nSeparating people who want to help from people that want to help themselves. Everyone can have a role.\n\nSocial Coding for Good helps with Hackathons.\n\n1. You need to have structure and onboarding path ahead of time.\n2. Lots of people want to be recognized. Volunteers need to be thanked. Their emotions need to be managed.\n\nA lot of volunteer newcomers. If it doesn\'t happen for them then it\'s unlikely they\'ll come back.\n\nCan you tap into universities? Really only if its part of a structured environment and it starts before the disaster.\n\nHow can you make tools useful and resilient in a disaster. \n\nA good way to do this is to experiment but how do you do that in a crisis scenario?\n\nOpen Architecture Network was trying to build a library of humanitarian designs for humanitarian projects. OS dev for buildings. Interactions that spans multiple incidents.\n\nHow do you let people use the tools they want and sort it out later? Answer: HXL-style approaches. As well as HDX system.\n\nWorld Bank funded Katmandu Living Labs to map Nepal because it was vulnerable. When the earthquake happened their work was very useful. Public Labs is another group that has datasets prone for environmental issues. FEMA could use then to make use of their data. Citizen science + Response. Crisis Cleanup spun up a common operating picture so groups could share info. \n\nNew Zealand story: CB radio tree.\n\nBay area earthquake zone. If there were a terrifying tsunami CERT would be there. Or NERT in the bay area. Neighborhood/Community Emergency Response Team. You should join them?\n\nIs there a guide of roles and responsibilities for disaster response? Maybe we need a book for this?\n\n4 things to do:\nmicrotasking\nmaking your tools useful and resilient\nPrep work who will benefit from your data.\nMap of the digital response ecosystem.\n... and a public communication plan\n\nIs remote volunteer crisis response useful? Yes! But lets never assume the same thing is always useful.\n\nMaybe we could have more of a \"book sprint\" approach to emergency planning?\n\nThe power of visualization.','recmvW2gZiRgmO8n8, rec9nelsOzk2AwHnk','','','','',''),(667,'recPKIqmXWSiJRxzY','NYCPrepared Knowledge Base','Challenges','You can find hundreds of pages of information about grassroots relief and resilieince tools and techniques within this website.  You can also add your own information (tools, stories, and more) and even influence the system\'s data structure.','recrePRKuyqvfJVcy, recR19V6gfOhjPJ8X, recBDtFLgpkjfAFc0','','','','',''),(668,'recCx8KzhwRtjKiNK','NYCPrepared Sites','Challenges','The goal of NYCPrepared Sites is to give your own website that makes sharing actionable information (such as requests for supplies and volunteers) your peers and partners as easy as possible.','recrePRKuyqvfJVcy, recqUlP97FkvZhwEB','','','','',''),(669,'recrePRKuyqvfJVcy','NYCPrepared Tools','Tags','Building a resilient community that can mitigate the risk of disaster and disruptions requires an uncommonly high level of coordination between